### Conserved RNA Structures in the SARS-CoV 2 genome

#### Introduction

**Abstract**

Severe acute respiratory syndrome related coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV2), which is responsible for the current global pandemic, is a positive strand RNA virus under the genus Betacoronavirus. The genome of SARS-CoV-2 is unique among viral RNAs in its potential to form stable RNA structures, but the structure of a vast majority of its 29 kb genome remains to be explored. Many RNA viruses utilize −1 programmed ribosomal frameshifting (−1 PRF) to robustly replicate and infect host cells, and SARS-CoV viruses exhibit a three-stemmed pseudoknot which facilitates exactly this. The function of these and other elements are unknown, but are highly structurally homologous both within SARS-CoV-2 and other coronaviruses, indicating selective pressure, and are thought to play a role in replication, and so holds potential as a small-molecule therapy target.

#### Methods

A complete reference genome for SARS-CoV-2 was accessed from NCBI Ref Seq (NC_045512.2) using Entrez, which included a selection of annotated features. To supplement this, metadata of samples submitted to nextstrain were downloaded, which are displayed alongside the GC content in Figure 1 and used to compute aggregate metrics in Figure 4. However, this has its flaws, and ideally a multiple sequence alignment would be performed to obtain a reference sequence and quantify variance.

Following this, we found the minimum free energy secondary structures of the RNA using the RNAfold^2^ tool. Due to the polynomial-time nature of the RNAfold algorithm, and moreso computing the partition function, the coronavirus genome was divided into the smallest structural units (protein coding regions) and folded separately, and even quantifying the structural stability via a measure of minimum free energy was infeasible even under this scheme. However, it seems that this was reasonable, as these non-overlapping segments coverred the entire genome less 109 basepairs, and it is known much of the secondary structure of SARS-CoV-2 consists of independent stem-loops.

In lieu of more advanced analyses, I first sought to understand the relative location of various annotated structures in a whole-genome context. In addition to the postscript renderings made by RNAfold, I explored two additional tools: the Python libraries forgi^1^, a secondary structure manipulation and visualization tool also from the ViennaRNA project, and DNAFeaturesViewer, a tool to visualize annotated genomic features. Ultimately, I did not end up generating figures with forgi, as it did not have an option to render RNAs with a linear "exterior loop" section but would instead treat the RNA segment as a standalone strand, despite otherwise being easier to grasp. Instead, I used the RNApuzzler layout algorithm^3^ included in RNAfold which does have this desired feature, though forgi might still be useful to perform analyses which treat secondary structure as a graph.

#### Results

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

**Figure 1**. (a) Annotated SARS COV 2 genome (orange=genes, green=peptide). The vertical green and orange bars correspond to the areas featured in figures 2 and 3, respectively.

Coronaviruses have ssRNA genomes that harbor two long open reading frames (ORF) which occupy around two-thirds of the genomic RNA, followed by several ORFs that are expressed late in the viral replication cycle. In general, the immediate early proteins encoded by ORF1a are involved in ablating the host cellular innate immune response, whereas the early proteins encoded in ORF1b are involved in genome replication and RNA synthesis. ORF1a and ORF1b are separated by a -1 PRF.

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 2. The coronavirus frameshift stimuation element, an example of a Programmed -1 Ribosomal Frameshift.

The −1 PRF signal can be broken down into three distinct parts: the “slippery site”, an attenuator loop, and a downstream stimulatory region of high secondary structure, typically a H-type pseudoknot. The primary sequence of the slippery site is `N NNW WWZ`, where `NNN` is a 3-mer of three repeating nucleotides, `WWW` is either `AAA` or ` UUU`, and Z ≠ G, a pattern which allows the transcribing tRNA to spontaneously "slip" by one base in the 5' direction. The attenuator region is shorter and more virus-specific, and the downstream secondary structure is meant to enable elongating ribosomes to halt, a necessary condition for efficient −1 PRF^10^. While these features are recognizable in Figure 2, there were many sequences which matched the 7-mer pattern, and it's not clear (at least from my research) what distinguishes a "true" stem loop.

![img](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 3. Various annotated RNA structures found in the 3' UTR.

The 3' UTR subregion shown above contains other notable elements known as the [coronavirus 3′ UTR pseudoknot](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_3′_UTR_pseudoknot) and the [coronavirus 3′ stem-loop II-like motif (s2m)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_3′_stem-loop_II-like_motif_(s2m)). Other structural motifs found to be important across coronaviruses are the [SL-III cis-acting replication element (CRE)](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Coronavirus_SL-III_cis-acting_replication_element_(CRE)&action=edit&redlink=1) and the [coronavirus packaging signal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_packaging_signal), and many more which might warrant a comparative analysis.

#### Discussion

Due to time constraints, and not being able to collaborate with other students, I was not able to perform many analysis which would either would be able to validate previous findings, or shed more light on the phenomenon of secondary structure in the coronavirus genome.

First, the choice of RNAfold as the secondary structure predictor was warranted due to its battle-tested status, there are arguably better choices. For one, computing the whole-genome structure, and even the full partition function on moderate subsections, proved to be infeasible, and might be improved with algorithms that take advantage of heirarchical folding^4^ or structural homology methods. Additionally, an in-vivo experiment^6^ found some, albeit minor, discrepancies, which suggests that assay data could improve the accuracy of the predictions.

Secondary structures are largely unannotated, and if they are, are difficult to compare in the case of a mutation. One potential avenue is investigating other ways to quantify secondary structure for the purposes of comparison, aside from MFE. Additionally, the extent to which secondary structure of RNA viruses is important for their function still remains to be answered, and it might therefore be useful to explicitly model ie viral replication or translation rates using assay data to better understand the life cycle of the virus.
